<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-10-04T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-10-04T22:00:00-05:00" n="806" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d806">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">511.4C1/58: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-10-05T12:00:00+09:00">October 5,
                                1933—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received October 5—12:33 a.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>151. Department’s instruction No. 358, September 11, 1933, Convention of
                        Saint Germain-en-Laye. Foreign Office states Japanese Government willing to
                        inform French Government that Japanese Government has no objection to the
                        understanding upon which the United States ratified the convention provided
                        we ask in an official note that this be done. Is there any objection to my
                        doing so?<note n="11" xml:id="d806fn11">Telegram No. 91, October 9, to the
                            Ambassador in Japan reads: “Please do so.”</note>
                    </p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>